<font color="#FF0000">TO NURSE RATCHET</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb  8  3:52:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Nurse Ratchet<br>
&gt;I don't think very many protestors spit on, cursed, hated, etc., returning vets. Surely, the ones that did were<br>
covered by the media. But there must have been 1,000 or more<br>
who protested simply by marching, sitting in, or writing letters for every one of those jerks who carried NV flags, spat, etc.&lt;<br><br>
&gt;....by 1970 (?) 80% opposed the war&lt;<br><br>
Maybe I'm(WE)using the wrong term.  Maybe &quot;protestor&quot; isn't the word to be used here.  Maybe &quot;protestor&quot; is a metaphor, such as the phrase, &quot;we were spat upon&quot;.  Reading your post brought this to mind as I reviewed the events of my return from 'Nam through the years.  The verbal abuse from an airline attendant and her subsequent refusal to serve me a meal on the flight from San Fran to Honolulu, the flipping the &quot;finger&quot; and the &quot;FUCK YOU's&quot; directed at me from civilians at the Honolulu airport, not once, but several times.  The difficulting obtaining a taxi to drive me home where I could shed the god-forsaken class A uniform.  The trip to a high school buddy's home who was then sharing a house with three others whom wanted to beat the shit out of me as soon as they learned I've just returned from 'Nam.<br><br>
And not twenty four hours had lapsed since I left San Francisco. Not three days after I left my platoon in the bush.<br><br>
Skip down memory lane to 1980, some eleven-twelve years later, eight years after the US pulled out of 'Nam. Working as a paramedic, two new employees arrive, buddy-buddy with each other, letting it be known that they were &quot;Born Again&quot;. Within two weeks they find out I was a medic in 'Nam, and literally, with a bible in one hand, and clenched fist in another, they tried to back me in a corner demanding that I tell them if I killed anyone in 'Nam, and if I did admit to such, they were going to kick my fucken ass! Why? Because killing is a sin!<br><br>
I won't get into anymore, just wanted to illustrate that in these instances, none were in a organized protest setting, sitting in, writing letters or marching.  I have no way of finding out, nor do I care, if they were representative of a established political group.<br><br>
I believe that there were many, many, people who protested in the manner of which you speak.  I also believe that these same people did not entice anyone to abuse the returning vets.  However, these acts did occur, with regular frequency and in varying degrees and to many, many vets.  And over a span of many years!  Why do you think many of us had hid in the woodwork as long as we have.  Because many of us were tired of the confrontations, tired of trying to explain why each of us went.  All we wanted to do was return to a life that we fantasized while in the muck of the war.  That fantasy included being &quot;normal&quot; and being a part of the society and community where we reside.<br><br>
Many of us were tired of the blood, guts and the bodycount system.  I used to be an avid bow hunter before 'Nam.  Used to go on extended hunting trips about five times a year.  In the first month when I returned, I went on another one.  I couldn't wait till I was out of there and never hunted again.<br><br>
Maybe it was as you said.  In 1970(?), 80% oppose the war.  Maybe those who committed these acts were from the 80% and not from the less than the 1/2 of 1% of those that participated in the organized demonstrations and rallys. This makes the veterans claims all that much more credible. These people and the subsequent events that vets endured were not covered by the media.  They certainly were not in my case.<br><br>
Nurse Ratchet, I have never, in all the posts that I have directed to you, ever gave you any Bullshit.  Believe me now.  I definitely was &quot;spat upon&quot;!
